Heaut. i. 2. 25: Ovid, Epist. xi. 53. AEschinus here gives a very great proof of his discretion. When any thing alarms us suddenly, or we see ourselves injured in the opinion of one we have a value sor, it is the hardest matter in the world to check the impatience we feel of being justified; nor are we apt, in such a case, to regard the con- sequence. But AEschinus, however anxious he was to remove his Pamphila’s suspicions, is yet too discreet to do it at the hazard of his brother's repose.— 17.
